</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kYHfwS lkFAWj pf-21_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-22_ pf-text-1">According to the World Health Organisation (WHO), approximately 422 million people worldwide have diabetes, with the number expected to rise.


</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-24_ pf-text-1">Diabetic emergencies, such as hypoglycemia (low blood sugar) and hyperglycemia (high blood sugar), can lead to serious complications if not addressed promptly.






</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-26_ pf-text-1">Studies suggest that up to 6% of people with diabetes will experience a severe hypoglycemic event each year.


